WEBVTT

00:08.225 --> 00:12.316
- [breathing rapidly]
- [shoveling]

00:15.580 --> 00:17.408
[gasps]

00:17.539 --> 00:20.150
[breathing heavily]

00:22.805 --> 00:25.460
[man grunting]

00:31.683 --> 00:35.426
[shoveling
and grunting continue]

00:45.306 --> 00:47.047
[gasps]

00:51.573 --> 00:53.488
- [knocking on door]
- Sara!

00:53.618 --> 00:56.273
Open the door!

00:56.404 --> 00:59.624
[woman] Stop it!
Robert, you're not well!

00:59.755 --> 01:02.323
[Robert] I need the boy!
No!

01:02.453 --> 01:04.673
Don't let him in.
Don't let him in...

01:04.803 --> 01:06.631
- [pounding, crashing]
- [gasps]

01:06.762 --> 01:10.679
[struggling, shouting]

01:12.681 --> 01:15.292
- No!
- [woman shouting]

01:17.555 --> 01:20.210
[woman cries, man roars]

01:24.649 --> 01:26.564
- Stop!
- Run!

01:26.695 --> 01:28.262
[man roars]

01:37.706 --> 01:40.187
[breathing heavily]

01:53.852 --> 01:55.680
Charles.

01:58.683 --> 02:00.468
Charles...

02:02.557 --> 02:03.645
Charles!

02:12.697 --> 02:15.135
[Charles] Christ in quiet,
Christ in danger,

02:15.265 --> 02:18.312
Christ in mouth
of friend and stranger.

02:19.356 --> 02:20.575
No!

02:20.705 --> 02:22.229
No, Father, no!

02:22.359 --> 02:24.666
No!

02:24.796 --> 02:27.277
Father, no, no!

02:27.408 --> 02:28.626
Father, stop! Wait!

02:28.757 --> 02:30.367
Father!

02:30.498 --> 02:32.326
On your knees, Charles.

02:32.456 --> 02:34.632
No! Father!
You're not well!

02:35.590 --> 02:37.287
It's coming.

02:37.418 --> 02:39.333
The worm.

02:39.463 --> 02:41.465
I can't stop it.

02:41.596 --> 02:42.814
Father, why?

02:42.945 --> 02:45.513
Blood calls blood, son.

02:45.643 --> 02:47.297
No!

02:53.738 --> 02:57.264
♪♪♪

03:01.616 --> 03:02.573
[gunshot]

03:14.933 --> 03:17.371
[breathing shakily]

03:19.111 --> 03:20.809
[woman]
You have to go, Charles,

03:20.939 --> 03:22.680
far away,

03:22.811 --> 03:24.682
and never return.

05:09.047 --> 05:11.615
[man]
Truly, truly, I say to you,

05:11.746 --> 05:13.791
he who believes in Him
who sent Me

05:13.922 --> 05:15.837
has eternal life

05:15.967 --> 05:17.969
and does not come
into judgement

05:18.100 --> 05:20.885
but has passed out of death
into life.

05:21.016 --> 05:24.541
[woman] Charles,
have you thought about it?

05:27.022 --> 05:28.850
A ship is no place
to raise children,

05:28.980 --> 05:30.852
especially our girls.

05:33.028 --> 05:34.769
[Charles] You never felt
that way before.

05:34.899 --> 05:37.511
[woman]
It's different now.

05:37.641 --> 05:40.514
The children will need a home,

05:40.644 --> 05:41.776
and school.

05:41.906 --> 05:44.474
Structure.

05:48.173 --> 05:50.524
I know
what you're afraid of,

05:50.654 --> 05:53.440
but you are not your father.

05:56.007 --> 05:58.009
You will know what to do.

05:58.140 --> 06:01.448
God sent us a gift
in your cousin's letter.

06:05.713 --> 06:07.758
"And whosoever liveth
and believeth in me

06:07.889 --> 06:09.499
shall never die."

06:17.899 --> 06:20.945
[girls weeping]

06:23.861 --> 06:28.692
[wailing and shouting]

06:31.129 --> 06:32.827
Captain.

06:34.785 --> 06:36.874
Is there something
you'd like to add?

06:37.005 --> 06:40.530
[girls cry]

06:44.882 --> 06:45.883
Set course for New London.

07:04.772 --> 07:05.599
[splash]

07:14.303 --> 07:16.827
[men shouting indistinctly]

07:33.061 --> 07:33.844
[Charles' father]
Blood calls... blood.

07:33.975 --> 07:36.760
[line repeating, overlapping]

07:36.891 --> 07:37.848
[roars]

07:39.894 --> 07:41.635
[breathing heavily]

07:49.077 --> 07:50.600
[man] Here we go.

07:53.255 --> 07:55.910
[indistinct chatter]

08:04.005 --> 08:07.269
[Honor] It's okay, Tane.
There's no scratching.

08:07.399 --> 08:10.141
There's nothing
to be afraid of. Okay?

08:10.272 --> 08:12.492
[Charles clears throat]

08:14.102 --> 08:16.017
Trouble sleeping?

08:16.147 --> 08:18.802
Tane's scared.
He heard scratching on the hull.

08:18.933 --> 08:20.804
He thinks Mother wants
to come back aboard.

08:20.935 --> 08:22.763
What if we put her
in the water alive?

08:24.155 --> 08:26.027
I assure you, son,
we didn't.

08:30.858 --> 08:32.773
Loa?

08:34.296 --> 08:36.559
She hasn't spoken all day.

08:43.740 --> 08:46.656
Children, uh...

08:46.787 --> 08:49.790
I have something
to share.

08:49.920 --> 08:55.099
We've inherited a sawmill
and a house in Maine

08:55.230 --> 08:58.015
from my cousin Stephen,

08:58.146 --> 09:01.236
a man I barely knew.

09:01.366 --> 09:04.979
He said he wanted to heal
an old rift in our family.

09:05.109 --> 09:08.983
Even has a name:

09:09.113 --> 09:10.811
Chapelwaite.

09:12.987 --> 09:15.032
[Honor]
We're getting off the ocean?

09:15.163 --> 09:16.686
[Charles] Aye.

09:18.906 --> 09:20.560
Your mother thought it best.

09:23.171 --> 09:34.051
♪♪♪

10:35.330 --> 10:37.288
You said it was a house.

10:37.419 --> 10:39.334
This is a mansion.

10:39.464 --> 10:41.205
How rich was your family?

10:41.336 --> 10:42.859
It's twice as big as a whaler!

10:46.254 --> 10:48.125
What do you think, Loa?

10:50.432 --> 10:52.782
I hardly know what to say
myself.

10:59.180 --> 11:01.182
You must be Charles Boone,
the sea captain?

11:01.312 --> 11:03.271
- I am.
- I'm Mrs. Cloris,

11:03.401 --> 11:05.273
the former housekeeper
of Chapelwaite.

11:05.403 --> 11:07.492
Stephen's executor asked me
to greet you

11:07.623 --> 11:09.843
and give you these papers
for the house and mill.

11:09.973 --> 11:11.322
Well, thank you.

11:11.453 --> 11:13.150
I'm afraid my absence

11:13.281 --> 11:15.283
has left the house
victim to vandals.

11:15.413 --> 11:18.895
Though it would seem
nothing was taken.

11:19.026 --> 11:22.203
Well. These are my children--

11:22.333 --> 11:26.076
Honor. Loa. Tane.

11:26.207 --> 11:28.209
Is there a Mrs. Boone
coming?

11:29.601 --> 11:31.821
My wife passed
eight months ago.

11:33.649 --> 11:35.303
Children, go on.

11:35.433 --> 11:37.000
Go explore.

11:43.441 --> 11:46.314
- Honor, look!
- Look at the staircase.

11:46.444 --> 11:49.317
You knew
my cousin Stephen then.

11:49.447 --> 11:52.059
Since he was a baby.

11:52.189 --> 11:54.931
His father,
Phillip, hired me.

11:55.062 --> 11:57.281
I considered Stephen my own.

11:57.412 --> 11:59.240
How did he die?

11:59.370 --> 12:01.285
Grief.

12:01.416 --> 12:04.201
We all carry grief.
It's rarely fatal.

12:06.334 --> 12:10.164
Stephen's daughter, Marcella,
meant everything to him.

12:10.294 --> 12:12.340
She fell down the cellar stairs.

12:12.470 --> 12:15.169
Broke her back into pieces.

12:15.299 --> 12:18.738
Stephen found the child
and never recovered.

12:21.697 --> 12:24.482
The door to the cellar
is in the kitchen.

12:24.613 --> 12:27.050
You'll find it locked. I
recommend you keep it that way.

12:27.181 --> 12:30.140
The stairs are dangerous.
It's no place for children.

12:33.187 --> 12:34.884
Um...

12:36.320 --> 12:39.149
Mrs. Cloris,

12:39.280 --> 12:41.499
in case you'd like to stay on,
we're in need of a governess.

12:41.630 --> 12:44.372
Thank you,
but I have no interest

12:44.502 --> 12:45.982
in being
in this house any longer.

12:46.113 --> 12:48.202
- If it's money--
- It's not.

12:48.332 --> 12:50.552
Hmm.

12:50.682 --> 12:53.903
I'll ask in town and return
with a few girls to clean.

12:54.034 --> 12:56.427
I owe Stephen that much.

12:56.558 --> 12:59.213
Preacher's Corners is an hour
east down the Post Road.

12:59.343 --> 13:01.955
You'll find all manner
of provisions there.

13:02.085 --> 13:04.871
[birds singing]

13:07.569 --> 13:09.179
Whip-poor-wills.

13:10.050 --> 13:12.356
I've never seen them
during the day.

13:19.407 --> 13:28.372
♪♪♪

13:41.168 --> 13:42.430
[glass clinking, rolling]

13:45.346 --> 13:47.000
Tsk...

13:49.437 --> 13:51.178
[sighs]

13:57.271 --> 13:59.229
[sighs]
Shit.

14:03.190 --> 14:05.322
That's cousin Stephen.

14:05.453 --> 14:08.369
I recognize him.

14:08.499 --> 14:10.023
[Loa]
Who's the little girl?

14:13.243 --> 14:17.030
She must be Marcella.
Stephen's daughter.

14:17.160 --> 14:18.422
Shouldn't this house be hers?

14:20.163 --> 14:21.425
She passed away.

14:24.559 --> 14:30.043
And that's Stephen's father,
Uncle Phillip.

14:30.173 --> 14:32.697
Ah, he was a stern man.

14:32.828 --> 14:35.352
They came to visit us
once in Massachusetts.

14:35.483 --> 14:39.139
They had wealth, standing.

14:40.749 --> 14:44.231
Stephen was always nice to me.

14:44.361 --> 14:47.234
When they left, I...

14:47.364 --> 14:49.279
I wanted to leave with them.

14:49.410 --> 14:52.543
How did they make
their fortune?

14:52.674 --> 14:55.546
My great-grandfather James
used to mine copper

14:55.677 --> 14:57.679
in the hills around here.

14:57.809 --> 15:01.378
My grandmother Silence
built upon that with lumber.

15:01.509 --> 15:03.511
How come you never talk
about your father?

15:07.341 --> 15:09.299
He was a...

15:09.430 --> 15:12.259
peculiar man, my father.

15:16.263 --> 15:19.048
Nothing more worth mentioning.

15:20.093 --> 15:23.444
Come, let's explore the rest
of the house, shall we?

15:34.672 --> 15:36.631
Children?

15:36.761 --> 15:38.372
I'm just stowing
some things down in the cellar.

15:54.649 --> 15:57.260
[door creaks]

16:11.666 --> 16:13.494
[exhales in disgust]

16:50.270 --> 16:51.140
[coughs]

17:14.337 --> 17:15.425
[grunts quietly]

17:41.582 --> 17:51.548
♪♪♪

18:08.652 --> 18:12.352
[creaking]

18:24.494 --> 18:27.236
[gasps]

18:36.593 --> 18:38.508
[door creaks]

18:41.642 --> 18:43.600
Those stairs aren't safe.

18:43.731 --> 18:45.733
No one goes down there.

18:45.863 --> 18:47.604
Understand?

18:47.735 --> 18:49.737
- Tane?
- Yes, sir.

18:49.867 --> 18:52.870
- [sighs]
- Um...

18:53.001 --> 18:55.612
Mrs. Cloris left us some food.

18:55.743 --> 18:58.441
Chicken and a loaf of bread.

19:01.009 --> 19:03.185
Oh, bless you, Mrs. Cloris.

19:05.666 --> 19:07.755
I think we're going
to like it here.

19:07.885 --> 19:09.452
Mm.

19:09.583 --> 19:11.411
I wish Mom could have seen
this house.

19:11.541 --> 19:13.282
I do, too.

19:15.937 --> 19:18.374
What do you think, Loa?

19:18.505 --> 19:19.767
Would your mother approve?

19:21.769 --> 19:24.641
Well.

19:24.772 --> 19:26.643
You may be right.

19:28.950 --> 19:32.432
She would've found Chapelwaite
extravagant.

19:32.562 --> 19:35.609
I agree with that, but, uh,

19:35.739 --> 19:39.917
I'm proud of it, too.
It's, uh...

19:40.048 --> 19:44.313
it's a symbol of
Boone industry and success.

20:06.814 --> 20:08.468
[rattling, creaking]

20:16.171 --> 20:19.696
[rattling, scurrying]

20:30.794 --> 20:33.754
[rattling, scurrying continue]

20:46.027 --> 20:48.377
What do you need, Loa?

20:51.859 --> 20:53.730
I'm afraid we have rats.

21:09.224 --> 21:12.532
They're being clever now.
They know we're onto them.

21:31.986 --> 21:37.470
[insects and birds chirping]

21:46.217 --> 21:48.002
Any luck?

21:48.132 --> 21:50.700
It's a bit confusing, sir.

21:50.831 --> 21:52.920
I didn't see no crappin's,
no holes.

21:53.050 --> 21:54.965
Just a couple
a dried-up carcasses.

21:55.096 --> 21:57.881
Well, we have rats,
Mr. Fletcher, I assure you.

21:58.012 --> 22:00.449
Maybe set those upstairs.

22:00.580 --> 22:01.842
All right.

22:46.669 --> 22:47.844
[gasps]

22:50.847 --> 22:56.984
[whip-poor-wills chant]

22:57.114 --> 22:59.508
[Tane, screaming]
Honor! Loa!

23:20.877 --> 23:22.618
I guess
this is where you go

23:22.749 --> 23:24.533
after the portrait gallery.

23:26.317 --> 23:28.537
Shouldn't they be
in a cemetery?

23:28.668 --> 23:30.147
[sighs]

23:30.278 --> 23:34.891
Not necessarily.
This was their home.

23:35.022 --> 23:37.590
They loved it and wanted
to be buried here;

23:37.720 --> 23:39.722
it's their choice.

23:39.853 --> 23:41.420
I don't like it.

23:43.117 --> 23:46.555
Come.
Let's go to town.

23:48.644 --> 23:57.436
♪♪♪

24:12.059 --> 24:15.628
How's the writing coming?

24:15.758 --> 24:17.107
I've got
a hundred bad ideas

24:17.238 --> 24:19.762
and not a single good one.

24:19.893 --> 24:22.112
Emerson writes
for the Atlantic Monthly.

24:22.243 --> 24:23.984
So do Longfellow and Stowe.

24:24.114 --> 24:27.117
[sighs] Who am I?

24:27.248 --> 24:29.119
Rebecca Morgan,
and you're a writer.

24:29.250 --> 24:31.295
You always have been.

24:31.426 --> 24:33.036
I believe in you;

24:33.167 --> 24:34.951
so does this editor,
Mr. Lowell.

24:35.082 --> 24:37.693
Yeah, but an entire story
in only four weeks?

24:37.824 --> 24:39.956
It's too much pressure.

24:40.087 --> 24:43.133
I'm making a coffin liner
for the Albrikes family.

24:43.264 --> 24:46.006
Old Gerald succumbed
to the illness yesterday.

24:46.136 --> 24:47.964
Maybe you should
write about that?

24:48.095 --> 24:49.618
Are those the new Boones?

24:51.925 --> 24:53.970
Good day.

24:59.062 --> 25:00.716
I'll meet you back
at the house, Mother.

25:00.847 --> 25:02.762
- Please.
- No, Rebecca, wait!

25:12.815 --> 25:15.035
Have faith, Rose.

25:15.165 --> 25:16.689
Edward.

25:16.819 --> 25:18.865
Your daughter will pull through.

25:18.995 --> 25:22.564
With all respect, Minister,
your wife lost two of her own.

25:22.695 --> 25:24.044
Treating illness with faith
doesn't give me much comfort.

25:34.228 --> 25:37.318
What does "quarantine" mean?

25:37.448 --> 25:40.930
"Quarantine" means there's
someone very sick inside.

25:41.061 --> 25:43.237
Well, what do we have here?

25:43.367 --> 25:45.413
I don't know what they are.
They sure ain't white.

25:45.544 --> 25:47.894
Probably fled the reservation.

25:48.024 --> 25:50.810
Was he talking about us?

25:50.940 --> 25:53.247
- He was.
- Why?

25:53.377 --> 25:57.338
Well, because...
because you don't look like him.

25:57.468 --> 26:01.211
He wants you to feel embarrassed
about being different.

26:01.342 --> 26:03.170
Now, if everyone's finished
shopping,

26:03.300 --> 26:04.127
let's meet
in front of the bakery.

26:04.258 --> 26:05.738
Can we each get a cookie?

26:07.827 --> 26:10.046
You can each have two. Go.

26:10.177 --> 26:11.744
[children laughing]

26:22.189 --> 26:24.060
Good day. May I speak with
the constable, please?

26:24.191 --> 26:25.758
George!

26:25.888 --> 26:27.716
Someone to see you.

26:30.980 --> 26:32.939
Constable.

26:33.069 --> 26:35.202
My name is Charles Boone.

26:37.813 --> 26:38.684
Is it?

26:38.814 --> 26:40.294
Yes.

26:40.424 --> 26:43.210
Um, my family and I moved

26:43.340 --> 26:44.994
into our home yesterday
at Chapelwaite

26:45.125 --> 26:47.823
and, um, we found it ransacked.

26:47.954 --> 26:50.217
Floors were torn up,
the furniture broken.

26:50.347 --> 26:54.134
People here don't like
Chapelwaite, Mr. Boone.

26:54.264 --> 26:56.615
So they're free
to vandalize it?

26:58.181 --> 27:01.010
If I were you,
I would sell the mill.

27:01.141 --> 27:03.273
Take what you can and go.

27:03.404 --> 27:05.275
Well, I have other plans.

27:05.406 --> 27:07.408
You might think twice
with children.

27:07.538 --> 27:11.020
What's going on here,
constable?

27:11.151 --> 27:13.196
Your family has a reputation,
Mr. Boone.

27:13.327 --> 27:17.418
Stephen was a part of that,
as was his father Phillip.

27:17.548 --> 27:22.075
They were strange,
unpredictable men.

27:22.205 --> 27:23.903
Not good people.

27:26.340 --> 27:30.170
I'm afraid you'll find few
friends in Preacher's Corners.

27:34.043 --> 27:36.089
They practically
threw a parade

27:36.219 --> 27:37.786
when your cousin
hanged himself.

28:20.307 --> 28:22.222
Tane.

28:22.352 --> 28:23.223
What are you doing?

28:25.007 --> 28:25.878
There's a ball.

28:26.008 --> 28:27.836
Come out of there.

28:31.622 --> 28:33.842
- Someone killed my bunny.
- [gasps]

28:36.976 --> 28:37.933
Did you do this?

28:38.064 --> 28:39.979
No!

28:40.109 --> 28:42.242
Father gave her to me
when I got sick.

28:42.372 --> 28:44.940
- You're sick?
- Tane! Come here!

28:47.638 --> 28:49.989
- What's wrong with her?
- I don't know.

28:51.599 --> 28:53.819
Stay back.
She's not well.

28:57.474 --> 28:59.259
- Oh, Susan!
- Stay away, kids.

29:01.478 --> 29:03.219
You are not to be out.
You know that.

29:09.356 --> 29:16.189
♪♪♪

29:24.240 --> 29:25.328
[horse snorting]

29:29.158 --> 29:31.117
- What is it, boy?
- [horse snorting nervously]

29:38.472 --> 29:39.908
[Mrs. Cloris]
Mr. Boone?

29:42.476 --> 29:44.130
The girls have finished
cleaning.

29:46.306 --> 29:47.829
Thank you.

29:50.136 --> 29:52.399
Um... Have you spoken
with the girls

29:52.529 --> 29:54.357
about the governess position?

29:54.488 --> 29:57.883
I have.
None are inclined.

30:00.494 --> 30:02.017
Mrs. Cloris.

30:04.150 --> 30:08.502
You said that
Stephen died of grief.

30:08.632 --> 30:11.592
I would have preferred
you were more specific.

30:11.722 --> 30:15.291
If you heard Stephen took
his own life, that's true.

30:15.422 --> 30:18.425
I was only trying
to protect his reputation.

30:18.555 --> 30:21.080
Thank you for that.

30:22.298 --> 30:25.345
This is a sad house, Captain.

30:25.475 --> 30:28.478
No Boone has ever
been happy here.

30:28.609 --> 30:31.960
Well, we'll be the first.

30:46.496 --> 30:48.629
Can I help you?

30:48.759 --> 30:52.415
Mr. Boone,
my name is Rebecca Morgan.

30:52.546 --> 30:55.592
I hear you're looking
for a governess.

30:55.723 --> 30:58.508
We are. Are you experienced
with children?

30:58.639 --> 31:00.989
I was one myself once.

31:04.514 --> 31:08.562
But I also lived with a family
while studying in Massachusetts.

31:08.692 --> 31:12.261
I helped with the children
in exchange for room and board.

31:12.392 --> 31:15.003
Wonderful.
Well, please come in.

31:16.570 --> 31:18.572
I must warn you,

31:18.702 --> 31:21.923
my two daughters and son all
have equal say in who we hire.

31:24.360 --> 31:26.449
And another part of my job

31:26.580 --> 31:28.321
would be to supplement
your education.

31:28.451 --> 31:30.366
If you've never been
to school,

31:30.497 --> 31:32.194
you may benefit from a bit
of extra tutoring.

31:32.325 --> 31:34.327
Mother taught us mathematics
and how to read.

31:34.457 --> 31:36.503
Oh, you learned from the Bible?

31:36.633 --> 31:39.332
She did. We read the Brontes
and Hawthorne.

31:39.462 --> 31:43.336
- Hm.
- And "The Three Musketeers."

31:43.466 --> 31:47.601
"Never fear quarrels,
but seek hazardous adventures."

31:47.731 --> 31:52.432
I believe you and I may share
the same adventurous spirit.

31:52.562 --> 31:54.695
There are subjects
to explore

31:54.825 --> 31:58.133
that you may not be exposed
to in Preacher's Corners.

31:58.264 --> 32:00.657
Philosophy, art, music.

32:00.788 --> 32:03.225
I learned those at college.

32:03.356 --> 32:06.054
I didn't know
women could go to college.

32:06.185 --> 32:07.751
They can.

32:07.882 --> 32:11.755
I went to Mount Holyoke
in Massachusetts.

32:11.886 --> 32:15.498
How about we make a deal?
I'll introduce you

32:15.629 --> 32:17.544
to some of the things
I learned in college

32:17.674 --> 32:20.242
and you can teach me
about your culture

32:20.373 --> 32:22.331
and all the wonders
you've seen.

32:26.379 --> 32:31.210
[Rebecca and the children
chatter indistinctly]

32:36.737 --> 32:38.130
[Rebecca and the children
laughing]

32:55.756 --> 32:59.238
I hope I have the opportunity
to get to know you all better.

33:06.288 --> 33:08.377
- Father?
- Mm.

33:08.508 --> 33:09.988
Come in.

33:17.734 --> 33:20.346
- Well?
- I don't think Loa wants her.

33:20.476 --> 33:22.391
Loa?

33:22.522 --> 33:24.176
You have a say in this.

33:24.306 --> 33:26.308
Just have to voice it.

33:30.399 --> 33:31.835
All aye?

33:31.966 --> 33:34.403
[Tane and Honor] Aye.

33:34.534 --> 33:36.014
All opposed?

33:41.019 --> 33:43.108
Well, the ayes have it.

33:54.380 --> 33:56.860
Thank you
for the opportunity.

33:56.991 --> 33:59.646
And I'll return in the morning
with my things.

33:59.776 --> 34:01.735
My kids, uh,

34:01.865 --> 34:04.781
they know books and ships,

34:04.912 --> 34:09.830
but they'll require more help
than they think navigating land.

34:09.960 --> 34:13.312
Um, Mr. Boone,
your daughter Loa.

34:13.442 --> 34:16.445
- The quiet one...
- She speaks.

34:16.576 --> 34:19.057
Not since her mother passed.

34:21.581 --> 34:24.192
I imagine she will
when she's ready.

34:25.411 --> 34:26.760
I should accompany you.

34:26.890 --> 34:29.284
- It's--it's late.
- Oh, I'm fine.

34:29.415 --> 34:32.331
[whip-poor-wills chant]

34:35.551 --> 34:37.075
Whip-poor-wills.

34:38.989 --> 34:41.470
- Good night, Mr. Boone.
- Good night.

34:58.531 --> 35:02.230
[rattling, scurrying]

35:10.630 --> 35:16.288
♪♪♪

35:16.418 --> 35:19.117
[rattling, scurrying resume]

35:33.522 --> 35:37.352
[rattling, scurrying resume]

35:42.749 --> 35:46.448
[rattling, scurrying resume]

36:08.078 --> 36:10.516
[Rebecca] The chant
of the whip-poor-will

36:10.646 --> 36:12.344
is the voice
with which the man

36:12.474 --> 36:14.172
and the house call her.

36:17.784 --> 36:20.569
- An omen of death, they say.
- [footsteps]

36:20.700 --> 36:22.702
Flee the nightjars' cry
or risk--

36:22.832 --> 36:24.834
Rebecca.
I want to talk to you.

36:24.965 --> 36:27.533
- It's late, Mother.
- I know where you were.

36:27.663 --> 36:29.926
I've been hired as the
new governess of Chapelwaite.

36:30.057 --> 36:32.712
Why would you do that? You...

36:32.842 --> 36:34.627
I sent you to college

36:34.757 --> 36:36.716
so you could make
something of yourself.

36:36.846 --> 36:40.372
You--you have an assignment
for the Atlantic Monthly.

36:40.502 --> 36:42.461
Don't squander this opportunity.

36:42.591 --> 36:44.593
I'm not.
I already telegraphed my idea

36:44.724 --> 36:46.508
to Mr. Lowell
and he approved it.

36:50.164 --> 36:53.385
There's only one good story
in town, Mother.

36:53.515 --> 36:55.691
Rebecca,

36:55.822 --> 36:58.912
you do not want to
make trouble with that family.

36:59.042 --> 37:01.523
You may not believe everything
that's said,

37:01.654 --> 37:03.743
but you'd be a fool
to ignore it. Your father--

37:03.873 --> 37:05.658
Father was
Phillip Boones' lawyer

37:05.788 --> 37:08.487
and he lived in fear
of the man. I am aware.

37:08.617 --> 37:11.533
You have to trust me.
I know what I'm doing.

37:11.664 --> 37:13.448
Good night, Mother.

37:17.800 --> 37:19.498
[Mother sighs]

37:27.549 --> 37:30.639
[metal scraping]

37:39.996 --> 37:41.824
Excuse me, young man,
what's your name?

37:41.955 --> 37:43.652
Able Stewart.

37:44.740 --> 37:47.047
You've been keeping the ledger
since my cousin's death.

37:47.177 --> 37:49.702
You must be
the new Mr. Boone.

37:49.832 --> 37:52.444
- I am.
- It's nice to meet you, sir.

37:52.574 --> 37:53.967
Pleasure to meet you.

37:54.097 --> 37:56.709
I've tried keeping
the records best I can.

37:56.839 --> 37:59.538
Sorry 'bout my writin'.
I taught myself.

38:00.974 --> 38:03.455
Well, I appreciate
your efforts.

38:06.893 --> 38:10.200
Which one of these men
is Daniel Thompson?

38:10.331 --> 38:12.594
It's the large man
on the right.

38:12.725 --> 38:14.466
Good. [clears throat]

38:19.949 --> 38:21.908
Foreman, uh, Daniel Thompson.

38:22.038 --> 38:23.692
That's me.

38:26.129 --> 38:28.784
I run this crew of vagabonds.

38:30.786 --> 38:32.484
You're the Captain?

38:32.614 --> 38:34.834
Uh, "Mr. Boone" will do.

38:34.964 --> 38:37.184
According to the ledger,

38:37.315 --> 38:41.710
board feet are down 60%
since my cousin's passing.

38:41.841 --> 38:43.669
Why aren't these men
out working?

38:43.799 --> 38:46.802
Well, they were.
This is our break.

38:48.238 --> 38:49.457
Ah.

38:51.154 --> 38:53.722
It's also noted that, uh,

38:53.853 --> 38:55.985
everyone has seen
a wage increase...

38:56.116 --> 38:59.467
all except
for Able Stewart here.

38:59.598 --> 39:01.774
Why is that?

39:01.904 --> 39:03.776
I really couldn't tell you
now.

39:11.087 --> 39:13.525
What's this?

39:13.655 --> 39:15.440
Your severance.

39:15.570 --> 39:17.355
Take it and leave.

39:20.793 --> 39:23.709
Or cut me 600 board feet
by end of today

39:23.839 --> 39:26.015
and every day hereafter.

39:26.146 --> 39:28.975
That an order, "Captain"?

39:30.672 --> 39:32.718
I give orders at sea.

39:32.848 --> 39:34.676
On land I give choices.

39:37.810 --> 39:39.986
Listen clearly, now.

39:40.116 --> 39:42.031
I have plans for this mill.

39:42.162 --> 39:44.207
We're expanding.

39:44.338 --> 39:46.862
From here out,
we run this mill like a whaler.

39:46.993 --> 39:49.778
Profit is gonna be divided
into a 100-part lay.

39:49.909 --> 39:51.563
Loggers earn two parts.
Foreman three.

39:51.693 --> 39:53.652
Owner takes 30.

39:53.782 --> 39:56.524
The more you cut,
the more you earn.

39:56.655 --> 39:58.396
Questions?

40:01.181 --> 40:02.835
Well, then, get to work.

40:04.837 --> 40:07.013
[indistinct chatter]

40:07.143 --> 40:08.841
What's the lay
for the tool keep, sir?

40:08.971 --> 40:11.234
One lay.

40:11.365 --> 40:14.542
Add another two
for keeping the ledger.

40:15.891 --> 40:20.374
I noticed some unpaid bills
charged to Jerusalem's Lot.

40:20.505 --> 40:21.897
Is that not my family's
old mining town?

40:22.028 --> 40:24.030
It is.

40:24.160 --> 40:25.901
Huh.

40:26.032 --> 40:27.729
Thank you, Able.

40:36.608 --> 40:39.959
If you'd like, I can help you
make scary costumes

40:40.089 --> 40:41.830
for All Hallow's Eve?

40:41.961 --> 40:43.963
- What can we be?
- Anything.

40:44.093 --> 40:47.183
Ghouls, ghosts, gypsies.

40:47.314 --> 40:50.230
What do we do
on All Hallow's Eve?

40:50.360 --> 40:53.842
Oh, we walk door to door
in town

40:53.973 --> 40:56.018
and people give us
money and food.

40:56.149 --> 40:58.760
Oh, and there's also games.

40:58.891 --> 41:01.197
One of them is, um,
with mirrors

41:01.328 --> 41:03.025
where you can see
your future husband.

41:03.156 --> 41:05.071
Another is with a pendulum

41:05.201 --> 41:07.465
where you can speak to spirits.

41:11.120 --> 41:13.601
That's my favorite.

41:14.646 --> 41:18.911
Now, the idea is that the
pendulum leads us to a spirit.

41:19.041 --> 41:24.786
And if we see a spirit,
it has to grant us a wish.

41:24.917 --> 41:29.095
If we know the spirit,
can we speak to it?

41:30.705 --> 41:31.924
Of course.

41:33.969 --> 41:36.276
North, south, east, west,

41:36.406 --> 41:39.235
wake up, spirit,
from your rest.

41:39.366 --> 41:42.717
Winter, spring, summer, fall.

41:42.848 --> 41:45.764
Let us see you, hear our call.

41:48.157 --> 41:49.898
This way!

41:53.989 --> 41:56.688
Let us see you, hear our call!

41:58.211 --> 42:00.518
This way.
Keep an eye out.

42:03.738 --> 42:05.784
Shh...

42:06.959 --> 42:08.787
Do you see anything?

42:19.798 --> 42:21.669
Anything?

42:21.800 --> 42:22.714
- Boo!
- [all scream]

42:22.844 --> 42:23.976
[laughs]

42:24.106 --> 42:25.107
I'm sorry! I'm sorry.
I had to.

42:25.238 --> 42:26.544
[gasping in relief]

42:30.199 --> 42:32.027
Did a spirit do that?

42:33.986 --> 42:35.814
It's just a draft.

42:41.036 --> 42:41.863
- [bird cry, thud]
- [gasps]

42:41.994 --> 42:43.648
What was that?

42:45.084 --> 42:47.129
Whip-poor-will.

42:47.260 --> 42:49.871
Oh, poor thing.

42:50.002 --> 42:51.873
[metallic chiming]

42:56.225 --> 42:57.139
That door's supposed
to be locked!

43:02.362 --> 43:04.190
Something's down there.

43:04.320 --> 43:06.366
[Tane]
I don't like this game.

43:06.496 --> 43:08.107
And that's all it is.
Just a game.

43:18.204 --> 43:19.858
Mr. Fletcher?

43:25.864 --> 43:26.908
[door slams]

43:34.307 --> 43:35.917
Let's go back to the parlor.

43:40.356 --> 43:45.884
♪♪♪

43:51.150 --> 43:53.935
[Rebecca]
What is a ghost?

43:54.066 --> 43:56.372
Is it a presence
that prowls our bed chambers

43:56.503 --> 43:58.200
when we turn down the lights?

43:58.331 --> 44:00.159
Or is it a memory

44:00.289 --> 44:02.814
that roams the dark corridors
of our mind?

44:02.944 --> 44:05.120
- [knocking]
- One moment.

44:19.134 --> 44:21.006
- Ah.
- Mr. Boone.

44:21.136 --> 44:22.964
May I speak with you
privately?

44:23.095 --> 44:25.010
Of course.

44:31.233 --> 44:34.454
Uh, I've reprimanded
Mr. Fletcher

44:34.584 --> 44:37.022
for leaving
the cellar door unlocked.

44:37.152 --> 44:39.372
- Oh.
- But I'm...

44:39.502 --> 44:42.854
I still have three children
very afraid in their beds.

44:42.984 --> 44:45.030
Oh. [sighs]

44:45.160 --> 44:46.901
I see.

44:47.032 --> 44:49.164
Miss Morgan, I am aware

44:49.295 --> 44:51.863
you're trying to bond
with the children,

44:51.993 --> 44:53.908
and I appreciate that, but...

44:54.039 --> 44:56.215
well, they're still acclimating

44:56.345 --> 44:59.044
to the loss of their mother
and the new house.

44:59.174 --> 45:02.177
And, well, perhaps no more

45:02.308 --> 45:05.267
games associated
with spirits or ghosts.

45:05.398 --> 45:08.444
I was trying to share
a little seasonal fun,

45:08.575 --> 45:11.317
but my efforts were misguided.

45:11.447 --> 45:14.668
- I'm sorry.
- Thank you. No.

45:14.799 --> 45:16.235
- Good--good evening.
- Mr. Boone.

45:16.365 --> 45:19.325
Tomorrow is Sunday.

45:19.455 --> 45:21.283
Yes.

45:21.414 --> 45:25.418
I was wondering
if we might consider

45:25.548 --> 45:28.203
taking the children to church?

45:28.334 --> 45:30.162
I don't think so.

45:30.292 --> 45:32.730
I'm not one for religion
myself.

45:32.860 --> 45:35.254
The church is a frequent
tool of intimidation

45:35.384 --> 45:37.256
and promotes
the repression of women.

45:37.386 --> 45:40.346
But this is small-town Maine,

45:40.476 --> 45:43.305
and people talk.

45:43.436 --> 45:47.353
Sir, your children
are wonderful,

45:47.483 --> 45:50.095
but I know what it's like
to be unique

45:50.225 --> 45:54.273
in a town that doesn't always
favor individuality.

45:54.403 --> 45:57.058
Sometimes it's easier to fit in.

45:59.365 --> 46:01.933
Well... you may be right.

46:03.543 --> 46:06.372
Thank you, Miss Morgan.

46:10.724 --> 46:13.422
- [church bell ringing]
- [indistinct greetings]

46:13.553 --> 46:15.947
- Good morning, Grace.
- Good morning, Alice.

46:16.077 --> 46:17.165
How are you?
Good morning.

46:19.385 --> 46:21.430
Hat off, thank you.

46:21.561 --> 46:24.085
Good morning.

46:24.216 --> 46:25.739
Good morning, Alice.

46:25.870 --> 46:27.567
I'd like to introduce you
to Charles Boone

46:27.697 --> 46:29.961
- and his children.
- How do you do?

46:30.091 --> 46:32.572
Ah, my name is
Alice Burroughs.

46:32.702 --> 46:35.270
My husband is minister
of this congregation.

46:35.401 --> 46:38.404
Nice to meet you.

46:38.534 --> 46:40.493
My father would like
to speak with you.

46:40.623 --> 46:44.018
This used to be his church.

46:45.411 --> 46:47.152
All right.

46:47.282 --> 46:50.590
Please, this way.

46:50.720 --> 46:52.026
We'll wait.

46:59.381 --> 47:02.950
Captain, this is my father,
Samuel Gallup.

47:03.081 --> 47:04.430
Sir.

47:04.560 --> 47:06.301
Mr. Boone.

47:06.432 --> 47:08.477
How do you do?

47:08.608 --> 47:12.003
My father noticed that
there isn't enough seating

47:12.133 --> 47:13.700
for our regular members,

47:13.831 --> 47:16.834
some of whom are quite old.

47:19.619 --> 47:21.447
We're happy to stand.

47:21.577 --> 47:22.970
It isn't that.

47:25.538 --> 47:27.322
You're asking us to leave?

47:27.453 --> 47:30.978
Mr. Boone, your children...

47:31.109 --> 47:32.153
are they Christian?

47:36.941 --> 47:39.334
They are as much
or as little Christian

47:39.465 --> 47:41.597
as they choose to be, sir.

47:41.728 --> 47:45.166
We prayed we'd seen
the last Boone.

47:47.168 --> 47:48.866
And why is that?

47:48.996 --> 47:52.043
Because your family
is a plague on this town.

47:56.177 --> 47:58.440
Well, that'll be enough, sir.

47:59.702 --> 48:03.402
Now, I don't know what happened
between you and my family,

48:03.532 --> 48:07.449
but neither myself nor
my children were a part of that.

48:10.583 --> 48:13.325
We want nothing more
than a fresh start here.

48:13.455 --> 48:16.371
I'm sorry to disappoint you.

48:16.502 --> 48:25.250
♪♪♪

48:25.380 --> 48:27.382
We're leaving.
Let's go.

48:27.513 --> 48:30.211
- Go! Tane!
- Did we do something wrong?

48:30.342 --> 48:32.039
Loa! Come! Now!

48:33.606 --> 48:36.565
- Loa! Come on! Now!
- [gasps]

48:36.696 --> 48:38.437
Shame on you.

48:48.664 --> 48:50.928
[door shuts]

48:56.368 --> 48:58.239
Sorry about church.

48:59.719 --> 49:01.373
That's not your fault.

49:03.288 --> 49:07.683
Samuel Gallup called
my family a plague.

49:07.814 --> 49:10.425
Samuel Gallup is
a crabby old Puritan.

49:10.556 --> 49:13.167
Hmm.
It's more than that.

49:17.606 --> 49:21.393
Some blame Chapelwaite
for the illness in town.

49:21.523 --> 49:24.222
The first afflicted were
two stable hands

49:24.352 --> 49:25.614
who worked here for your cousin.

49:25.745 --> 49:28.704
Both died.
That was two years ago.

49:28.835 --> 49:32.491
Since then, five have been
planted in the church graveyard.

49:32.621 --> 49:35.494
But that's hardly proof.

49:35.624 --> 49:38.410
If it were,
I wouldn't be here.

49:46.635 --> 49:49.116
What's Loa doing?

49:51.466 --> 49:53.512
She wants to be alone.

49:57.646 --> 49:59.126
So I should leave her then,
right?

50:01.302 --> 50:03.261
Absolutely not.

50:05.567 --> 50:07.265
Oh.

50:23.585 --> 50:25.457
[exhales]
I lost my temper earlier.

50:25.587 --> 50:28.547
I...

50:28.677 --> 50:31.637
I'm sorry. I shouldn't have
grabbed you like that.

50:31.767 --> 50:34.379
But you need to mind me.

50:38.426 --> 50:44.606
♪♪♪

50:54.529 --> 50:58.185
I understand why you blame me.

51:00.492 --> 51:02.494
I do.

51:05.758 --> 51:06.759
Your mother never
would've gotten sick

51:06.889 --> 51:08.674
if she'd stayed on the island.

51:11.851 --> 51:15.463
Your leg never would've
withered from rickets.

51:18.945 --> 51:25.430
But she was so strong,
your mother.

51:25.560 --> 51:30.435
She... insisted on coming.

51:33.568 --> 51:36.615
She demanded we were a family.

51:44.710 --> 51:47.104
I miss her, too.

51:49.410 --> 51:51.630
I miss her, but...

51:51.760 --> 51:55.242
you can't stay silent forever.

52:09.735 --> 52:15.697
There's something inside
that you hide from us.

52:18.570 --> 52:20.702
It scares me.

52:36.979 --> 52:40.592
When my father got sick,
Doctor Guilford said,

52:40.722 --> 52:43.638
"Burn his clothes.
Burn the bedding."

52:43.769 --> 52:47.642
Well, it didn't do shit,
but it was the right idea.

52:47.773 --> 52:50.428
Let's send these new Boones
packing

52:50.558 --> 52:52.560
before they inflict
their own wickedness on us.

52:52.691 --> 52:54.432
What about you, Edward?

52:54.562 --> 52:57.304
Your little Susan's sick.
Who's next?

53:00.786 --> 53:02.614
Burn it then.

53:08.924 --> 53:10.796
Do it.

53:25.463 --> 53:34.341
♪♪♪

53:40.434 --> 53:41.740
[grunts]

53:47.441 --> 53:49.400
[door squeaks]

53:49.530 --> 53:51.445
Susan!

53:51.576 --> 53:52.794
I need you to go back
in the house.

53:52.925 --> 53:54.448
It's cold out here.

54:05.720 --> 54:09.376
[whip-poor-wills chant]

54:14.816 --> 54:21.170
♪♪♪

54:21.301 --> 54:25.044
[Rebecca] I could leave tonight
and no one would fault me.

54:25.174 --> 54:27.176
I could fabricate
a pale fiction

54:27.307 --> 54:30.441
of these Boones
and their trial.

54:30.571 --> 54:32.921
Who would know but me?

54:33.052 --> 54:36.403
But therein lies the hook.

54:38.884 --> 54:40.842
For alone in the dark,

54:40.973 --> 54:44.803
me is who I answer to.

55:02.908 --> 55:05.606
Hidden within the crude
timbers of this dark manor

55:05.737 --> 55:07.739
lies the truth.

55:07.869 --> 55:10.568
I can feel it.

55:13.092 --> 55:14.615
Outside this house,

55:14.746 --> 55:16.878
fear gathers,

55:17.009 --> 55:21.622
and ignorance spreads from
home to home like the illness.

55:21.753 --> 55:23.755
[horses walking]

55:23.885 --> 55:26.888
[oil sloshing]

55:27.019 --> 55:33.330
[whip-poor-wills singing]

55:40.641 --> 55:42.600
[horse snorts]

55:42.730 --> 55:43.775
Who goes there?

55:55.090 --> 55:55.961
[grunts]

55:57.615 --> 56:00.357
[frantic breathing]

56:03.795 --> 56:05.492
[cries out]

56:16.155 --> 56:21.378
[man screams]

56:39.047 --> 56:42.964
[Rebecca] What drove this
bloodline to its tragic depths?

56:44.923 --> 56:48.405
Suicide, murder, madness.

56:49.623 --> 56:51.843
[sighs]

56:51.973 --> 56:54.193
[Rebecca] To know the truth
of Chapelwaite,

56:54.323 --> 56:57.675
I must know the mystery
of Charles Boone.

57:02.854 --> 57:04.595
[sighs]

57:29.924 --> 57:30.969
[glass breaks]

57:31.099 --> 57:33.058
[groans]

57:33.188 --> 57:38.455
[gasping]

57:42.110 --> 57:43.590
